This paper deals with the representation of graphs using circles, which is a topic in computational geometry (cs.CG). It also involves combinatorial aspects of graph theory, such as planarity and connectivity, which are relevant to discrete mathematics (cs.DM) and algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). The paper provides upper and lower bounds on the number of circles needed for a realization, which is related to graph theory and topology (cs.GT). Finally, the paper discusses an infinite class of graphs that do not admit circle representations, which is relevant to computational complexity and computational intractability (cs.SI).
